column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Security and Conflict']

The chance is very low given the current COVID situation in China and the global economic downturn. If you google "Wikipedia timeline of the South China Sea dispute", you will find that there was only one bullet point for the year of 2020, when China's economy was badly hit by COVID.

Not at the same time Russia is F_ing up the world economy and the Rapid response for the NATO States and EU sanctioning such Unrationed geopolitical carnages.
Slightly increased the probability. China might take advantage of the war in Ukraine, and America's focus on it, to test Taiwan's defenses.

Not unlikely, as China has been doing regular provocations towards Taiwan and the China Sea in the last two decades, more and more aggressively. However, such direct force confrontations are more Russian in style, which are conducting this type of operation in Ukraine, albeit much less efficiently. Taiwanese armed forces however are much more modern and prepared than Ukraine, and I do not see China starting this kind of operation unless the Ukrainian war resolves in a very victorious fashion for the Russians, which is far from being the case.

Going down a bit, China doesn't seem on board with Russia's activity after all and therefore cannot be relying on it as a cover for their own activities, which makes this less likely in the short term at least.

First forecast on this question. Starting quite a bit higher than the current crowd forecast, I'm also quite high on the question concerning China flying a plane over mainland Taiwan (https://www.gjopen.com/questions/2169-will-taiwan-publicly-accuse-the-people-s-republic-of-china-of-flying-a-military-aircraft-over-the-territory-of-and-or-the-territorial-waters-surrounding-the-main-island-of-taiwan-without-its-permission-before-1-september-2022).

Landing on the Pratas Islands will probalbly be seen as a serious violation of Taiwan's territory with the possibility of triggering US military involvement. The 20th Party Congress of the Communist party will be held in October 2022, it is very likely China would avoid a serious international conflict before this date.
no pick another fight

The clearest trigger for the PRC to make such a move would be a formal declaration of independence by Taiwan. Since Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen has stated that only majority public opinion can decide Taiwan's future and cross-strait relations (https://thediplomat.com/2021/09/taiwanese-presidents-will-not-and-can-not-unilaterally-change-taiwans-status/), it seems like a remote possibility (let's say <5%) that Taiwan will make substantive moves in this direction by 1 Jan 2023, given that prevailing Taiwanese public sentiment as recently as June 2021 is for a maintenance of the status quo.(https://esc.nccu.edu.tw/upload/44/doc/6963/Tondu202106.jpg: ~87% of respondents chose some variation of "Maintain status quo", compared to around 6% indicating "Independence as soon as possible". Even if we consider the 25.8% who indicated "maintain status quo, move towards independence" as being in favour of independence in the near future, those in favour of independence in the near-term are still considerably in the minority.)
China thinks in long term. The long term runs out by Jan. 2023
China is playing the long game, which means they'll wait for the perfect confluence of events to exert their hegemony over the Taiwanese.
Seems like this would trigger maximum antagonism for microscopic strategic gain.
Taiwan is very smart politically and will most likely not take a public accusation against the People's Republic of China due to the potential for more military back lash.

My initial instinct on this was very unlikely. However, I was caught off guard by something similar last year with the fighting in the Himalayas between Indian and Chinese forces, so I wonder if I'm biased in the wrong direction there.

Yes, these are uninhabited islands, located in the northern part of the south china sea, a quick look on the map and participants here will notice these a small islands and are at least 548 km from Taiwan so while occupying them servers no practical and strategical purpose it does give an opportunity to Chinese Govt and military to test American and allied forces military and civilian response. China knows any invasion, blockade, or limited military strikes on Kinmen and Matsu will bring in a swift response from Taiwan, America, and its allies.

Pratas Island itself is only 2.8km long. There are no permanent inhabitants. It is predominantly used by Taiwanese military personnel, researches, and fishermen.

Yes.As China government shows strong will to solve Taiwan's problem .2022 to 2024 maybe a good time to do this.Landing on Pratas can threaten Taiwan but not lead to total war. I think it maybe a good choice for PRC.
Seizing the islands doesn't get them much but would provoke a wider conflict. Costs of such a conflict clearly outweigh the benefits.
Because the limits will be pushed
Increased intimidation of Taiwan over the next 12 months is certainly likely so could be part of China's strategy.
Besides China looking for a 'nose to punch' re India, there is Pratas as well. China (in its reckoning) cannot abide the US continuing to shove China around SE Asia.

Doing so would probably spark a regional, and then much larger, conflict. I can see a scenario where the PRC makes some kind of excuse to land on the islands as a means to intimidate Taiwan. Realistically, there is no reason I can think of for the PRC military to land on Pratas unless as a precursor to a Taiwan invasion, which Taiwan's National Security Bureau director-general Chen Ming-tong says won't happen before 2024.

The Pratas Islands roughly is located between Taiwan & HK, and is about 400KM away from mainland Taiwan. Hence more vulnerable to the potential attack. However, a capture could lead to an all-out war between the island and the mainland. And there is a chance that the US gets involved as well. It's speculated that this would not happen during tenure of Taiwan's President - Tsai Ing-Wen. That is 2024. Since coming to the power in 2016 Tsai is determined to secure formal independence from China, hence the military activities & political intimidation from China.
